29
00:01:04,620 --> 00:01:05,260
him the option.

30
00:01:05,800 --> 00:01:08,340
This would be a call option to buy

31
00:01:08,340 --> 00:01:11,620
the house for $500,000, which is referred

32
00:01:11,620 --> 00:01:14,320
to as the strike price, anytime within the

33
00:01:14,320 --> 00:01:16,840
next three months, which is the expiration date.

34
00:01:17,260 --> 00:01:18,700
Now if he does not elect to buy

35
00:01:18,700 --> 00:01:21,720
the house, Susie keeps the $5,000 premium

36
00:01:21,720 --> 00:01:23,540
and Sammy walks away from the deal.

37
00:01:23,940 --> 00:01:25,700
If he does elect to buy the house,

38
00:01:26,140 --> 00:01:29,360
or exercise the option, Susie still gets to

39
00:01:29,360 --> 00:01:31,760
keep the $5,000 and he pays her

40
00:01:31,760 --> 00:01:33,800
$500,000 for the house.

41
00:01:33,800 --> 00:01:36,180
Now, three things could happen in this story.

42
00:01:36,800 --> 00:01:39,000
In Scenario 1, Peter buys the nearby parcel

43
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:39,420
of land.

44
00:01:39,880 --> 00:01:41,660
This of course will increase the value of

45
00:01:41,660 --> 00:01:44,880
Susie's home to say $600,000, in which

46
00:01:44,880 --> 00:01:47,160
case Sammy will be very happy to exercise

47
00:01:47,160 --> 00:01:49,420
his option to buy the house for $500

48
00:01:49,420 --> 00:01:49,840
,000.

49
00:01:50,900 --> 00:01:53,440
In Scenario 2, Harry buys the nearby parcel

50
00:01:53,440 --> 00:01:53,860
of land.

51
00:01:54,320 --> 00:01:56,140
This of course will decrease the value of

52
00:01:56,140 --> 00:01:59,260
Susie's home to say $400,000, in which

53
00:01:59,260 --> 00:02:01,920
case Sammy will not exercise his option to

54
00:02:01,920 --> 00:02:04,600
buy at $500,000 and he'll just walk

55
00:02:04,600 --> 00:02:06,860
away from the deal having lost only $5

56
00:02:06,860 --> 00:02:07,220
,000.

57
00:02:08,259 --> 00:02:10,640
Then there's Scenario 3 where neither party buys

58
00:02:10,640 --> 00:02:11,920
the nearby parcel of land.

59
00:02:12,420 --> 00:02:15,520
Susie's house is still worth $500,000 and

60
00:02:15,520 --> 00:02:17,720
Sammy can elect to exercise his option to

61
00:02:17,720 --> 00:02:20,160
buy the house for $500,000 or not

62
00:02:20,160 --> 00:02:22,560
and simply walk away from the deal losing

63
00:02:22,560 --> 00:02:23,620
only $5,000.

64
00:02:24,200 --> 00:02:27,420
In effect, Sammy is controlling a $500,000

65
00:02:27,420 --> 00:02:30,320
asset for three months for only $5,000.

66
00:02:30,820 --> 00:02:32,900
No matter what happens during that time, the

67
00:02:32,900 --> 00:02:34,820
most he can lose is $5,000.

68
00:02:35,580 --> 00:02:37,280
Susie on the other hand is happy to

69
00:02:37,280 --> 00:02:39,280
take the $5,000 as she had no

70
00:02:39,280 --> 00:02:41,300
guarantee anyone else would buy the house at

71
00:02:41,300 --> 00:02:43,600
her asking price, nor did she feel the

72
00:02:43,600 --> 00:02:45,720
nearby parcel of land would sell any time

73
00:02:45,720 --> 00:02:46,080
soon.

74
00:02:46,520 --> 00:02:47,980
Here's a footnote to this story.

75
00:02:48,400 --> 00:02:51,100
Depending on the circumstances, if Susie felt she

76
00:02:51,100 --> 00:02:53,340
was likely to attract another buyer in the

77
00:02:53,340 --> 00:02:55,680
near term, she would have demanded more than

78
00:02:55,680 --> 00:02:57,940
$5,000 from Sammy to take the house

79
00:02:57,940 --> 00:02:59,340
off the market for three months.

80
00:02:59,780 --> 00:03:02,700
Likewise with call options, the more the underlying

81
00:03:02,700 --> 00:03:06,120
asset is perceived to appreciate, the higher the

82
00:03:06,120 --> 00:03:08,360
premium demanded by the market for that call

83
00:03:08,360 --> 00:03:08,680
option.

84
00:03:09,300 --> 00:03:11,060
So now let's define this in trading terms

85
00:03:11,060 --> 00:03:13,040
and look at an actual example trade.

86
00:03:13,600 --> 00:03:15,580
A call option is a contract between two

87
00:03:15,580 --> 00:03:17,980
parties to exchange a stock at a strike

88
00:03:17,980 --> 00:03:19,520
price by a predetermined date.

89
00:03:19,520 --> 00:03:21,940
One party, the buyer of the call, has

90
00:03:21,940 --> 00:03:24,240
the right, but not an obligation, to buy

91
00:03:24,240 --> 00:03:26,540
the stock at the strike price by the

92
00:03:26,540 --> 00:03:29,080
future date, while the other party, the seller

93
00:03:29,080 --> 00:03:31,580
of the call, has the obligation to sell

94
00:03:31,580 --> 00:03:33,120
the stock to the buyer at the strike

95
00:03:33,120 --> 00:03:36,100
price if the buyer exercises the option.

96
00:03:36,680 --> 00:03:38,720
For example, if a stock is trading at

97
00:03:38,720 --> 00:03:40,480
$50 and you think it's going to go

98
00:03:40,480 --> 00:03:43,120
up to $60, you might buy a $55

99
00:03:43,120 --> 00:03:46,800
call option for say $0.20. If the

100
00:03:46,800 --> 00:03:49,420
stock rose to $60, that would allow you

101
00:03:49,420 --> 00:03:52,440
to buy the stock at $55 even though

102
00:03:52,440 --> 00:03:55,200
it's valued at $60 netting you a $4

103
00:03:55,200 --> 00:03:56,980
.80 profit on each share.

104
00:03:57,420 --> 00:03:59,180
On the other hand, the person that sold

105
00:03:59,180 --> 00:04:01,000
you the call would be obligated to sell

106
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:03,920
you the stock at $55 at a loss

107
00:04:03,920 --> 00:04:06,960
of $4.80. If the stock never rises

108
00:04:06,960 --> 00:04:10,480
above $55 by expiration date, the call expires

109
00:04:10,480 --> 00:04:13,140
worthless and the call buyer is out $0

110
00:04:13,140 --> 00:04:15,360
.20 and the call seller keeps the $0

111
00:04:15,360 --> 00:04:17,920
.20. Okay now let's look at how put

112
00:04:17,920 --> 00:04:21,060
options work by revisiting Susie and Sammy from

113
00:04:21,060 --> 00:04:22,160
our earlier story.

114
00:04:22,880 --> 00:04:24,960
Sammy owns a truck worth $40,000.

115
00:04:25,500 --> 00:04:27,520
He's concerned that his truck might be damaged

116
00:04:27,520 --> 00:04:29,120
in an accident or even stolen.

117
00:04:29,540 --> 00:04:32,000
So Sammy decides to buy a zero deductible

118
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:35,580
insurance policy, or a put option, on the

119
00:04:35,580 --> 00:04:37,760
truck for the full amount of $40,000,

120
00:04:38,180 --> 00:04:40,980
which would be the strike price, from Susie's

121
00:04:40,980 --> 00:04:42,120
auto insurance company.

122
00:04:42,620 --> 00:04:45,320
Susie charges him $1,500, that would be

123
00:04:45,320 --> 00:04:47,780
the option premium, for a one year policy.

124
00:04:48,240 --> 00:04:50,560
One year being the expiration date.

125
00:04:50,860 --> 00:04:52,920
Now three things could happen in this story.

126
00:04:53,500 --> 00:04:55,660
In the first scenario, Sammy's truck is not

127
00:04:55,660 --> 00:04:57,720
damaged or stolen during the year.

128
00:04:58,180 --> 00:05:00,260
So Susie keeps the $1,500 premium.

129
00:05:00,840 --> 00:05:03,160
Sammy's okay with losing the $1,500 for

130
00:05:03,160 --> 00:05:05,580
the protection it provided him for the year.

131
00:05:05,980 --> 00:05:08,940
In scenario two, Sammy's truck is damaged in

132
00:05:08,940 --> 00:05:12,820
an accident, requiring $10,000 in repairs.

133
00:05:13,420 --> 00:05:16,640
He exercises his insurance policy, or his put

134
00:05:16,640 --> 00:05:18,580
option, by filing a claim.

135
00:05:19,080 --> 00:05:21,260
And Susie pays him $10,000 for the

136
00:05:21,260 --> 00:05:22,520
repairs as agreed.

137
00:05:23,220 --> 00:05:25,980
Sammy is happy he purchased protection for this

138
00:05:25,980 --> 00:05:26,620
possibility.

139
00:05:27,300 --> 00:05:29,600
In the third scenario, Sammy's truck is stolen.

140
00:05:29,960 --> 00:05:33,080
He exercises his insurance policy, which is his

141
00:05:33,080 --> 00:05:35,740
put option, and files a claim, but this

142
00:05:35,740 --> 00:05:38,140
time for the full replacement value of his

143
00:05:38,140 --> 00:05:38,440
truck.

144
00:05:38,980 --> 00:05:40,680
And Susie pays him the full amount of

145
00:05:40,680 --> 00:05:42,400
$40,000 to buy a new truck.

146
00:05:42,920 --> 00:05:45,360
Sammy, of course, is very happy he purchased

147
00:05:45,360 --> 00:05:46,880
protection for this possibility.

148
00:05:47,580 --> 00:05:49,680
In any case, Susie's happy because she's sold

149
00:05:49,680 --> 00:05:53,380
many such insurance policies, different put options, to

150
00:05:53,380 --> 00:05:56,120
other drivers, most which never filed a claim

151
00:05:56,120 --> 00:05:59,860
or never exercised their options, providing her with

152
00:05:59,860 --> 00:06:01,040
a net profit overall.

153
00:06:01,660 --> 00:06:02,980
And here's a footnote to this story.

154
00:06:03,140 --> 00:06:05,620
If Sammy had a poor driving record, that's

155
00:06:05,620 --> 00:06:07,740
more risk to Susie, so she would have

156
00:06:07,740 --> 00:06:10,240
charged him more than $1,500 for the

157
00:06:10,240 --> 00:06:11,360
one-year insurance policy.

158
00:06:11,780 --> 00:06:13,020
On the other hand, if Sammy had an

159
00:06:13,020 --> 00:06:15,860
exemplary driving record, Susie could have charged him

160
00:06:15,860 --> 00:06:17,720
less as the risk would be lower.

161
00:06:18,240 --> 00:06:20,480
Likewise, with put options, the higher the perceived

162
00:06:20,480 --> 00:06:23,000
risk, the higher the premium demanded by the

163
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:23,240
market.

164
00:06:23,840 --> 00:06:26,040
Let's look again at a definition and a

165
00:06:26,040 --> 00:06:26,740
trading example.

166
00:06:27,220 --> 00:06:29,960
A put option, then, is a contract between

167
00:06:29,960 --> 00:06:32,620
two parties to exchange a stock, or an

168
00:06:32,620 --> 00:06:35,620
ETF, at a strike price by a predetermined

169
00:06:35,620 --> 00:06:35,900
date.

170
00:06:36,380 --> 00:06:38,360
One party, the buyer of the put, has

171
00:06:38,360 --> 00:06:40,560
the right, but not an obligation, to sell

172
00:06:40,560 --> 00:06:42,820
the stock at the strike price by the

173
00:06:42,820 --> 00:06:45,160
future date, while the other party, the seller

174
00:06:45,160 --> 00:06:47,560
of the put, has the obligation to buy

175
00:06:47,560 --> 00:06:49,580
the stock from the buyer at the strike

176
00:06:49,580 --> 00:06:51,640
price if the buyer exercises the option.

177
00:06:52,220 --> 00:06:54,080
For example, if a stock is trading at

178
00:06:54,080 --> 00:06:56,200
$50 and you think it's going to go

179
00:06:56,200 --> 00:06:58,900
down to $40, you might buy a $45

180
00:06:58,900 --> 00:07:02,340
put option for, say, $0.20. If the

181
00:07:02,340 --> 00:07:04,640
stock dropped to $40, that would allow you

182
00:07:04,640 --> 00:07:07,420
to sell the stock at $45 even though

183
00:07:07,420 --> 00:07:10,320
it's valued at $40, netting you a $4

184
00:07:10,320 --> 00:07:12,500
.80 profit on each share.

185
00:07:13,020 --> 00:07:14,820
On the other hand, the person that sold

186
00:07:14,820 --> 00:07:16,860
you the put would be obligated to buy

187
00:07:16,860 --> 00:07:18,980
the stock from you at $45 at a

188
00:07:18,980 --> 00:07:22,200
loss of $4.80. If the stock never

189
00:07:22,200 --> 00:07:25,380
drops below $45 by expiration date, the put

190
00:07:25,380 --> 00:07:28,240
expires worthless, and the put buyer is out

191
00:07:28,240 --> 00:07:30,660
$0.20, and the put seller keeps the

192
00:07:30,660 --> 00:07:33,540
$0.20. Thanks for watching this video and

